Boil a #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} for your noodles. Cut your @flank steak{1} into really thin ribbons. Coat this in the @cornflour{1%tbsp} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}.

> The cornflour is a natural tenderiser so your meat will be deliciously soft.

Slice the @red chilli{1} in half length-ways, remove the seeds and slice thinly. Thinly slice your @spring onions{3} diagonally and finely chop the @garlic clove{1}. Crush your @cashew nuts{1%handful}, cut the root off the @pak choi{1.5} and separate the leaves.

Put the @egg noodle nest{2} in the boiling water for ~{4%minutes} then drain them (the number of nests depends on how hungry you are!). Refill the pan with cold water, put the noodles back in and keep the pan to the side.

> This will stop them cooking and keep them from sticking together.

Heat up @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #non-stick pan{} on high heat until it is almost smoking. Fry the steak in small batches so that the outside is browned off but the inside remains rare. Take the meat out of the pan and keep to the side for later.

Add another @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} into the #pan{}. Fry off the chilli, spring onions and garlic for ~{2%minutes}. Add in the steak, @soy sauce{1%tbsp} and the @beef stock pot{1/2}. Add @water{100%ml}, the bok choy, @Chinese five spice{1%tsp} and @?sugar{1%tsp}.

Once the bok choy has wilted and the sauce has thickened up (which only takes ~{2%minutes}), add the noodles (once drained) back into the pan. Toss everything together with a good squeeze of @lime{1/2} juice.

To present the dish, simply put your noodles in a #bowl{}, grate on a little bit of lime zest and top with your crushed nuts.

Take two #chopsticks{} and wrap an #elastic band{} tightly around the ends to keep them together. Next, take a small piece of #paper{} and wedge this in between them so that you have essentially created a pair of tweezers. The height of HelloFresh technology!